This statement by the President on the 50th Anniversary of the War on Poverty highlights the progress made in the past 50 years and the challenges that still exist. The President mentions the creation of new avenues of opportunity through jobs and education, expanded access to healthcare, and support for working families. The statement emphasizes the importance of programs like Social Security and Medicare in reducing poverty rates among seniors. The President also acknowledges that there is still work to be done, with many children born into poverty and wages and incomes not rising for many Americans. The statement calls for redoubling efforts to ensure that the economy works for every working American by creating new jobs, improving wages and benefits, expanding access to education and healthcare, and providing opportunities for people to climb the ladder of success. The President emphasizes the importance of unity and promises to leave no one behind in the recovery and growth of the nation.